         <abstract>
            <p>Despite numerous attempts to identify a unique index of profitability, or decision criterion, for use in capital budgeting, no one candidate has been found to satisfy all users. This paper, following the adage that two heads are better than one, takes a bird's-eye view of the many possibilities and advantages of using more than one criterion; it reviews evidence that many financial analysts do in fact use multiple criteria; and it considers briefly the thorny question of how many criteria are worth using in practice.</p>
         </abstract>
